<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Reprieve (LAI 0066)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reprieve is a legal charity which works on death penalty cases around the world and human rights abuses committed as part of the ‘War on Terror.’  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reprieve has serious concerns about the range of proposals set out in ‘Transforming Legal Aid,’ but this ev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">idence will focus on the ‘residence test,’ as this has most direct relevance to our area of work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although slight changes to the proposals have been set out in the MoJ’s recent ‘Next Steps’ consultation, the fundamental problems remain.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">First, by denying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> access to legal aid for those not resident in the UK, the proposals will in many cases put the Government beyond the reach of the rule of law when it comes to its activities overseas.  Those who have been wronged by the activities of the UK Government ove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rseas will be denied the funding they need to secure legal redress.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Examples include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Anti-Gaddafi dissidents kidnapped and ‘rendered’ to torture in Libya, along with their wives and children.  Sami al Saadi (whose case was settled last year) and Abdelhak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">im Belhadj (whose case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> against the UK Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is ongoing) would, under the proposed residence test, be ineligible for legal aid in order to hold the Government accountable for its central role in their rendition and torture.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Civilian victims of US dron</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e strikes, carried out with the support of UK intelligence service GCHQ: Noor Khan, who lost his father to a drone strike on a peaceful local council meeting in North West Pakistan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and is currently bringing legal action against the UK Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, would sim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilarly be ineligible for legal aid under the proposed residence test.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Second, although the Government claims its aim is to exclude only those without a “strong connection to the UK,” the residence test will still shut out British citizens and residents si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mply because they are not in the country at the time of applying – a situation which may be unavoidable should they be detained overseas at the time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One notable past case which would have fallen foul of the residence test is that of Binyam Mohamed, who t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ook legal action against the UK Government over its complicity in the horrific torture which he suffered.  At the time, although he was a British resident, he was being detained without charge or trial in Guantanamo B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ay.  He would therefore have fallen fou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l of the proposed residence test, which only grants legal aid to those who “are lawfully resident in the UK, Crown Dependencies or British Overseas Territories </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">at the time the application for civil legal aid was made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> [emphasis added].”</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Third, the test will still shut out those who, although not resident in the UK, have provided significant services on behalf of the UK, and therefore should arguably considered to have a ‘strong connection.’  Notable examples include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The retired Gurkhas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who brought legal action under the last Government to secure the right to settle in the UK.  As they were retired, they would not have benefited from the proposed residence test exception for serving members of the Armed Forces.</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local interpreters who wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rked for British Forces during the war in Afghanistan but were denied asylum in the UK, who have subsequently sought to secure this through the courts.  Again, although they have worked on behalf of the UK in dangerous circumstances, and as a result are in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> some cases facing death threats, they will not qualify for the exception for those currently serving in the Armed Forces.</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The residence test will therefore, despite recent tweaks, still shut out deserving cases, including those brought by British citizens or those with clear links to the UK.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crucially, it will exempt much of the British Government’s behaviour overseas – wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere some of the most serious human rights abuses have taken place – from being held accountable through the courts.  It is worth noting that the Justice Secretary’s parallel moves announced earlier this year to introduce “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a tighter test for standing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further contribute to this effect.</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It therefore does not seem far-fetched to see in these measures an aim not merely to reduce costs – the Government itself </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has not identified any savings from the introduction of the residence test</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but rather to redu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce the ability of the public to hold the state accountable through the courts.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This is an alarming move, which cannot be justified on the grounds of savings, and must be resisted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Notes</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> For background, see e.g. ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Gurkha veterans claim victory in court battle for UK visas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,’ Guardian, 30 September 2008: </span><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/sep/30/military.immigration"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/sep/30/military.immigration</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> See ‘“Death threats”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> for Afghan interpreter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,’ BBC News, 3 May 2013: </span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22397689"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22397689</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> See ‘Judicial Review – Proposals for Further Reform,’ Ministry of Justice, September 2013, pp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">22-26,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">  available at: </span><a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/judicial-review"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://consul</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">t.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/judicial-review</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> On the absence of savings as a result of the residence test, see ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Civil credibility impact assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,’ Ministry of Justice, 9 April 2013, p2:  </span><a href